   <titles>
      <title>Distance of a Point from a Hyperplane – Illustration</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> and in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> we illustrate what we mean by ‘distance of a point from a hyperplalne’.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> a hyperplane is a line. So we will develop a formula which computes the distance of a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> from a line <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/DistancePointHyperplane_2D.gif" height="225" width="434"/>
                     <info>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Connections from <math>
                                 <latex>Q</latex>
                              </math> to points on <math>
                                 <latex>L</latex>
                              </math> have varying lengths. So what shall we mean by ‘distance of <math>
                                 <latex>Q</latex>
                              </math> from <math>
                                 <latex>L</latex>
                              </math>?</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Given a line <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> and a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>, there is always exactly one point <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math> on <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> which is closest to <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>. So we define the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> to be the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>In <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> a hyperplane is a plane in the conversational sense. So we will develop a formula which computes the distance of a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math> from a plane <math>
                     <latex>L</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para align="center">
               <para.body>
                  <media type="image" active="1" inline="0">
                     <img src="ims/DistancePointPlane01.gif" height="330" width="440">
                        <image.mapping>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="420,144,9">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The point <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="302,260,7">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The point <math>
                                          <latex>R</latex>
                                       </math> is the point on the plane closest to <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="poly"
                                 coords="5,3,3,325,437,325,437,165,419,165,363,301,203,257,71,157,31,67,49,47,177,81,275,103,271,89,81,3,13,5">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>The plane <math>
                                          <latex>\Pi</latex>
                                       </math> is given.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="149,117,14">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Other points on <math>
                                          <latex>\Pi</latex>
                                       </math> have a distance from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math> that is greater than the distance of <math>
                                          <latex>R</latex>
                                       </math> from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="93,151,12">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Other points on <math>
                                          <latex>\Pi</latex>
                                       </math> have a distance from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math> that is greater than the distance of <math>
                                          <latex>R</latex>
                                       </math> from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="52,70,9">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Other points on <math>
                                          <latex>\Pi</latex>
                                       </math> have a distance from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math> that is greater than the distance of <math>
                                          <latex>R</latex>
                                       </math> from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="224,250,9">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Other points on <math>
                                          <latex>\Pi</latex>
                                       </math> have a distance from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math> that is greater than the distance of <math>
                                          <latex>R</latex>
                                       </math> from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                           <area shape="circle" coords="355,287,10">
                              <info>
                                 <para>
                                    <para.body>Other points on <math>
                                          <latex>\Pi</latex>
                                       </math> have a distance from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math> that is greater than the distance of <math>
                                          <latex>R</latex>
                                       </math> from <math>
                                          <latex>Q</latex>
                                       </math>.</para.body>
                                 </para>
                              </info>
                           </area>
                        </image.mapping>
                     </img>
                  </media>
               </para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Given a plane <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> and a point <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>, there is always exactly one point <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math> on <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> whose distance from <math>
                     <latex>R</latex>
                  </math> is less than the distance of any other point on <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>. Thus we define the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> to be the distance from <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math> to the point on <math>
                     <latex>\Pi</latex>
                  </math> closest to <math>
                     <latex>Q</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
